380–1456","1390–Female":"1390–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","about 1360":"circa 1360","1403":"1403","about 1390":"circa 1390","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1417":"1417","1390":"1390","Ireland":"Ierland","Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1360–1417":"about 1360–1417","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1367–1403":"1367–1403","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1390–Female":"1390–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1403":"1403","about 1390":"about 1390","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1417":"1417","1390":"1390","Ireland":"Ireland","Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Neill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan, Dermot, Liam, Nuala, Bridie, Brigid, Conor, Fintan, John Patrick.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Néill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niall</i>’, an Irish personal name possibly derived from <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’ (see   Neil  ).","History: Bearers of this surname mostly claim descent from Niall Noígíallach (Niall of the Nine Hostages), a legendary king of Ireland who flourished in the 5th century. His descendants, the Ui Neill dynasty, dominated Ireland, on and off, from the 6th to the 10th century. The surname itself can be traced with some confidence to one of these descendants, namely Niall Glúndubh mac Aodha (died 919), High King of Ireland from 911 to 919, with a power base in Tyrone, Ulster."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Neall","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"McNelis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Niallghuis</b> ‘son of <i>Niallghus</i>’, a personal name (intended as complimentary) composed of the personal name <i>Niall</i> (see   O'Neill  ) + <i>gus</i> ‘vigor’. In Irish the combination of [k] and [n] was generally pronounced [kr], Anglicized as the variants   McCreless   and   McCrillis  ."]},{"name":"O'Neal","meanings":["Irish (Longford, Down): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"O'Niel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Odneal","meanings":["Perhaps an irregular variant of Irish   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Nealon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Nialláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niallán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Niall</i>, see   O'Neill  ,   Neil  ."]},{"name":"O'Neil","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conn, Donal, Liam, Siobhan, Aileen, Eamon, Michael Patrick, Seamus, Sean Patrick, William Sean.","Irish (Mayo, Tipperary): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Neil","meanings":["Scottish, English (Lancashire), and Irish (Munster): from the Gaelic personal name <i>Niall</i> (genitive <i>Néill</i>), possibly derived from Irish <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’. In most cases the name probably represents a shortened form of the derived patronymics   McNeill   or the comparable Irish   O'Neill  .","English: variant of   Neal  ."]},{"name":"O'Neel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]}]},{"name":"Una","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Úna . In Irish legend Úna is the mother of the hero Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles). It was also the name of the beloved of the 17th-century poet  Tomás Láidir Costello : banned by her parents from seeing him, Úna fell into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."],"variants":[{"name":"Euna","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Ùna ."]},{"name":"Oona","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Oonagh","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Juno","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Irish name Úna , assimilated to the name of the Roman goddess <i>Juno</i>, consort of Jupiter."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Una O'Neill was born about 1360, in Ireland as the daughter of Domnall O'Neill and Mrs. Domnall O'Neill. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with King Niall 'Og' O'Neill. She died in 1417, in her hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"about 1360–1417":"umbes 1360–1417","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1367–1403":"1367–1403","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1403":"1403","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1417":"1417","1390":"1390","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1360–1417":"noin 1360–1417","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1367–1403":"1367–1403","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","1403":"1403","about 1390":"noin 1390","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1417":"1417","1390":"1390","Ireland":"Irlanti","Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1360–1417":"environ 1360–1417","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1367–1403":"1367–1403","1380–1456":"1380–1456","1390–Female":"1390–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","about 1360":"environ 1360","1403":"1403","about 1390":"environ 1390","1456":"1456","1367":"1367","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1417":"1417","1390":"1390","Ireland":"Irlande","Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Irlande","lifeSummary":"U